		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//douthat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/10/19/liberal-catholicisms-catholicism-problem/" data-title="Liberal Catholicism&#8217;s Catholicism Problem" data-description="When a &quot;pastoral&quot; change has revolutionary implications.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/18/opinion/sunday/the-plot-to-change-catholicism.html?rref=collection%2Fcolumn%2Fross-douthat&amp;action=click&amp;contentCollection=opinion&amp;region=stream&amp;module=stream_unit&amp;version=latest&amp;contentPlacement=1&amp;pgtype=collection">Sunday column</a>Â wasÂ the latest installment in my strange, now year-old series of <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/26/opinion/sunday/ross-douthat-the-pope-and-the-precipice.html">Catholic critiques</a> of where my church&#8217;s supreme pontiff seems to want <a href="//douthat.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/10/30/a-church-not-a-party/">to take the faith</a>.Â But since the column was focused on church politicking and the mechanics of papal power, it seems worth trying to explain a little more why conservative Catholics are consistently un-reassured, in the ongoing argument in Rome over communion for the divorced and remarried, by our liberal co-religionists&#8217; insistence that nothing doctrinal, nothing beyond the &#8220;pastoral,&#8221; nothing essential to the church, is being opened for debate.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To try to clarify our fears, I&#8217;llÂ step back from the Roman fray for a moment and resume <a href="//americamagazine.org/issue/james-martin-and-ross-douthat-pope-francis-synod-and-demands-law-and-mercy">my old dialogue</a> with Father James Martin of the Society of Jesus, with whom I went a few rounds last fall on the question of where Catholicism is being steered under Pope FrancisÂ and whether that course is sufficiently, well, Catholic to be long sustained.Â Father Martin <a href="//time.com/4070048/catholic-church-inclusion/?xid=tcoshare">weighed in</a> on the synod recently with a piece for Time Magazine, entitled &#8220;The Catholic Church&#8217;s Inclusion Problem,&#8221; in which he framesÂ the debate over &#8220;how the church should treat divorced and remarried Catholics, LGBT Catholics, and other people who have felt shut out&#8221; with the following New Testament exegesis:</p>
<blockquote>
<p class="clipper--hidden">There are two main ways for a church to welcome people, and these approaches are exemplified by two figures in the Gospels &#8230;Â The first you could call the âJohn the Baptist method,â where the church asks for conversion as a prerequisite for joining the community. Even those with scant biblical knowledge can easily conjure up an image of John the Baptist, a fiery prophet wearing a camel-hair garments and eating locusts, passionately calling people to a âbaptism of repentance,â as the Gospel of Mark has it.</p>
<p class="clipper--hidden">Conversion meant a change of heart and a change of life that oriented one toward God. Only then were people ready to enter the reign of God. For John the Baptist, it was conversion first, community second.</p>
<p class="clipper--hidden">By contrast, there is what you might call the âJesus method.â</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="clipper--hidden"><span id="more-21287"></span></p>
<blockquote>
<p class="clipper--hidden">In the story of Zacchaeus in the Gospel of Luke, Jesus spies a man named Zacchaeus perched high in a sycamore tree. He was the chief tax collector in the region, which at the time would have also meant that he was considered the âchief sinnerâ in the region, since he was colluding with the hated Roman authorities. Jesus calls up to him, âZacchaeus, hurry and come down, for I must stay at your house today!â Zacchaeus shinnies down the tree and repents, saying that that he will repay anyone he has defrauded âfour times as much.â</p>
<p class="clipper--hidden">Jesusâs offer of welcome prompted Zacchaeusâs change of heart. For Jesus, it was community first, conversion second.</p>
<p class="clipper--hidden">Obviously these are simplifications of the complex ministries of John and Jesus &#8230;Â But in general, the two models are accurate: Johnâs emphasis was mainly on purification; Jesusâs mainly on mercy. They are also helpful templates when considering how the church approaches those on the margins, those who feel distanced from the church, those who have engaged in sinful behaviorsâin fact, everyone who feels excluded from the church.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8230;Â While both John the Baptist and Jesusâs methods are valid, in the end we need to remember why John the Baptist said of Jesus: âHe must increase and I must decrease.</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As applied to current controversies in the church, this argument almost perfectly illustrates why conservative Catholics are so &#8230; well, <em>unsettled</em> would be putting it mildly &#8230; by the claimsÂ being marshaled by would-be &#8220;pastoral&#8221; reformers in the age of Francis. And that&#8217;s despite the fact that as a very broad point about Christian ministry Father Martin&#8217;s argumentÂ is perfectly defensible.Â The idea, which he elaborates on further in the piece, that you often have to form a kind ofÂ community with people outside the faith in order to have any hope of bringingÂ them inside is a valuable piece ofÂ gospelÂ wisdom in and of itself; it&#8217;s also an important corrective to the tendency of conservative-to-traditional Catholicism to privilege the rules and rubrics of the faith, the internal practice for the already-converted, over a missionary spirit. And not only a missionary spirit: A spirit of charity, full stop, which canÂ indeed be absent from an overly legalistic, moralistic form of Catholic faith. (Read, for instance, <a href="https://www.commonwealmagazine.org/right-first-time">this account</a> of a divorced woman&#8217;s treatment by her pre-Vatican II parish for a sense of how cruellyÂ Catholic moralism can err.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On this kind of broadÂ question, as I tried to say in my original dialogue with Father Martin, a lot depends on reading the signs of the times. I think liberal Catholics are often still fighting a war they won after Vatican IIÂ when they charge the <em>contemporary</em> church (especially in the West) with being too purity-obsessed and insufficiently merciful, and that theological liberalism today risks erring so far on the side of mercy that it ends up excluding ideas of sin and conversion altogether. But when we&#8217;re talking about a general spirit, a general attitude, a general approach to outreach and evangelization, the proper response to a given cultural moment is one where reasonable Catholics can certainly disagree.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But the key debate at and around the synod in Rome right now is not a <em>broad</em> one about whether the church should look outward or look in, focus on missionary work or focus on its own internal rubrics.Â Nor is it a debate or whether parish priests should actively shun people in irregular relationships, or whether Catholic parents should invite their son&#8217;s same-sex partner or their divorced-and-remarried daughter&#8217;s second husband to Christmas dinner, or whether I should demand that my atheist friends recite the oath against modernism before I invite them to my house for supper, or any other social hypothetical you might consider.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">No: It&#8217;s a very specific debate aboutÂ whether conversion and repentance are necessary, not for community, but forÂ <em>communion</em>: The reception of the eucharist, the body and blood of Christ, during the central act of Catholic worship, the sacrifice of the mass.Â And by claiming â or at least very strongly implying âthat <em>Jesus&#8217;s meals with sinners</em> are the template for how the church should think about communion, Father Martin is effectively rejecting the entire sweep of our church&#8217;s tradition on this question.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This tradition is rooted in the gospels themselves, where the Last Supper is emphatically <em>not</em> a feeding of the five thousand moment or a meal with a tax collector: Those encounters are arguably prefigurations of theÂ Last Supper, but the actual eucharistÂ itself is instituted in an intimate encounter between Jesus and his closestÂ followers, held in a private upstairs room far from the crowds and hangers-on.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The tradition is also rooted in the New Testament more broadly, and particularly in Saint Paul&#8217;s admonition that &#8220;a man must examine himself first,Â and then eat of that bread and drink of that cup; he is eating and drinking damnation to himself if he eats and drinks unworthily.&#8221; (Which doesn&#8217;t sound like a &#8220;community first, conversion second&#8221; admonition to me.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And then it&#8217;s rooted in the ancient, millennia-spanningÂ practice of the church itself, in which the idea that communion followsÂ conversion is part of the chain of Â experience that binds the earliest Christians to their medieval and modern Catholic heirs.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So treating the eucharist as a form of outreach instead would represent a revolution, not a mere pastoral tweak, in the way the church thinks about that sacrament (and not only that one). That&#8217;s because there&#8217;s no clear way to confine Father Martin&#8217;s logic to the narrow cases at issue in this debate.Â If community precedes conversion in the reception of communion, why shouldÂ only remarried Catholics (or gay Catholics, or polygamous Catholics) have the benefits of being welcomed at the altar? The same welcoming logic would surely apply to any unshriven sinner in need of conversion. And not just any sinner who happened to be baptized Catholic: If the template is Jesus&#8217;s meals with the unconverted, then it would apply to any human being, period, since who <em>wouldn&#8217;t</em> Jesus have dined with? Why should Protestants not be welcomed to communion? Why shouldn&#8217;t Jews? (We know Jesus liked to dine with Jews!) Why shouldn&#8217;t Muslims and Mormons, agnostics and atheists? If the eucharist is basically a form of food-based Christian fellowship, a means toÂ outreach and welcome and hospitality rather thanÂ a sacred mystery for believers to approach with reverence and not a little fear, then forget the divorced and remarried; barring <em>anyone</em> from receivingÂ makes no sense at all.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And indeed there are many Christian churches that take exactly this attitude toward communion. But they are also, not coincidentally, generallyÂ churches that don&#8217;t have Catholicism&#8217;s view of transsubstantiation, confession, or the sacramental economy writ large. They are always Protestant, frequently liberal, and emphatically not the Roman Catholic Church in which both myself and Father Martin were confirmed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Which is, in the end, the crucial issue here. Of course Catholicism changes; of course Catholic teaching has altered in various ways across the centuries and millennia. But the changes that are being bruited about right now, in Rome and in the public writings of liberal Catholic writers, need to have their implications clearly stated. Their underlying logic would gradually usher in, not some sort of meatless-Friday pastoral changeÂ or a rhetorical shift toward mercy rather than condemnation, but a significant Protestantization of the church. They wouldÂ open a new chapter <a href="//douthat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/04/03/the-memory-of-catholicism/">in theÂ post-1960s iconoclasm of Catholic memory</a>, the very modern erasure of the Catholic Christian past.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Perhaps this is all just the unfolding will of the Holy Spirit, as Father Martin has recently taken to Twitter to suggest. Time will tell on that score. But it&#8217;s quite clearly the will, acknowledged or not, of many of the voices presently claiming that all they want is a mere &#8220;pastoral&#8221; change, and we would all be better off if more of them acknowledged honestly where such a change would ultimately take the church. And I am being completely sincere when I say that Father Martin&#8217;s fascinating New Testament exegesis is a welcome step toward that kind of transparency.</p>
	</div>
